After obtaining the FTDI converter, work began on migrating the project from the 
computer's built-in camera to the ESP32-CAM platform. First, the hardware connections 
between the FTDI module and the ESP32-CAM were completed. The power supply, TX and 
RX communication pins, and the IO0 programming pin were connected according to the 
manufacturer's documentation. The accuracy of the wiring was verified using a multimeter 
and wiring diagrams.

Next, the ESP32 board support package was installed in the Arduino IDE, and the ESP32-CAM
module was configured as the target development board. The required drivers were installed, 
and communication with the board was established through the serial port. Sample applications 
were uploaded to verify that the ESP32-CAM could be programmed successfully.

Afterward, the CameraWebServer example provided for the ESP32-CAM was uploaded to the board, 
and the wireless network connection was configured. The board was connected to the local Wi-Fi 
network, and its IP address was obtained through the Serial Monitor. The camera interface was 
then accessed through a web browser to test the live video stream. The successful operation of 
the ESP32-CAM was confirmed, and the next stage of integrating it with the Python application 
was planned.
